Lektionen, die heute aus der Kuba-Krise gelernt werden können
“Thirteen Days” („Dreizehn Tage“), ein neuer Film über die Kuba-Krise, wird bald in den Kinos zahlreicher Länder anlaufen.
Jeder sollte sich dieses Werk ansehen, nicht nur, da der Film die Vergangenheit aufarbeitet, sondern auch, weil er Einsichten in gegenwärtige Ereignisse bietet – insbesondere hinsichtlich der Kontroversen um ein US-amerikanisches nationales Raketenabwehrsystem und die verschiedenen regionalen Diskussionen in Indien und Pakistan, Taiwan und China, Nord- und Südkorea, die eines Tages in einem nuklearen Konflikt eskalieren könnten.
Am 16. Oktober 1962 hat Präsident John F. Kennedy seine engsten Berater im Weißen Haus zusammengerufen.
Luftaufnahmen der Region hatten den Bau einer Stationierung von Atomwaffen auf Kuba offenbart.
The decisions made during the following thirteen days, and those that were not reached, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened in the White House during these days.
Tape recordings made during President Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
Following the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard organized a discussion round to discuss both the film and the crisis it focuses on.
Participants in this round included: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a historian at Harvard who authored a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a political science professor at Harvard who presented a classic study on the Cuban Crisis, "Essence of Decision," thirty years ago.
Furthermore, Peter A. Almond, the producer of the film, was present.
Although the filmic adaptation of the topic was criticized at various points, the discussion participants agreed that the film portrays the problems and pressure that President Kennedy faced exactly as they were in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized it as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in a crisis, but ultimately it is only the President who bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – both civilian and military – wanted to attack Cuba at the time.
Only through Kennedy's calm analysis and his probing questions were alternatives and dangers revealed that were crucial in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; furthermore, communication channels must remain open.
Pushing an opponent into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open that allow understanding of the opponent's situation could prove disastrous.
· The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy acted accordingly because NATO, further allies, and the opinion of the world supported him.
· A certain period of time is needed for making good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to rush him into action.
The fact that a week passed during which all relevant factors were examined and weighed precisely was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a timeframe for deliberation even exist today given the current mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it is necessary to put oneself in the position of the opponent.
In one of the frequently criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade imposed by Kennedy on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intent, rather than being a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted more calmly?
Above all, the USA also had nuclear warheads stationed near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba merely reflected this policy.
But Kennedy showed concern about the consequences that the stationing of Soviet missiles in Cuba could have had for Berlin.
The pressure of weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Chruschtschow's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuba crisis," as historian Ernest May claimed.
"It will be too late soon," was a widespread argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba while they believed the rockets were still en route by sea to Cuba.
An approximately 180,000-strong US troop was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a blitz bombing campaign that would have been larger than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "I needed thirty years," said McNamara, "to find out that there were already nuclear warheads on Cuba: 162 warheads, and 90 of them strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If yes, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew about it.
I explicitly recommended using atomic weapons.
I knew that this would lead to the annihilation of Cuba."
Castro and, to a greater extent, his comrade Che Guevara were ready to reduce Cuba to ashes so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
An invasion would therefore potentially have led to the deaths of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because President Kennedy's government lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often occurs when a politician must make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion "would undoubtedly" have led to a Soviet nuclear attack against the USA.
Chruschtschov's control over the Soviet military on Cuba was limited: despite explicit contrary orders from the chairman, U2 aircraft flying over Cuban airspace were shot down.
A difficult question that was not raised during this Harvard debate is: What if the opponent had not been Chruschtschov, who distinguished himself during the crisis by rational behavior, but rather someone like Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the proliferation of nuclear weapons, this danger could become a reality someday.
Today's discussions about a limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in light of this terrifying but entirely realistic idea.
Harvard has posted a new website on the internet where the key documents about the Cuban Crisis as well as current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
